# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anthropogenic-metabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In layman's terms, anthropogenic metabolism indicates the human impact on the world by the modern industrialized world.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Much of these impacts include waste management, ecological footprints, water footprints, and flow analysis (i.e., the rate at which each human depleted the energy around them).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most anthropogenic metabolism happens in developed countries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A water footprint is the amount of water that each person uses in their daily lives.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most of the world's water is salt water which cannot be used in human food or water supplies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Therefore, the freshwater sources that were once plentiful are now being diminished due to anthropogenic metabolism of the growing population.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The water footprint encompasses how much fresh water is needed for each consumer's needs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Allan, "there is a huge impact of water use on stores of surface and groundwater and on flows to which water is returned after use.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] These impacts are shown to be particularly high for manufacturing industries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] For example, that there are less than 10 economies worldwide that have a significant water surplus, but that these economies have successfully met, or have the potential to meet, the water deficits of the other 190 economies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Consumers enjoy the delusion of food and water security provided by virtual water trade.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In addition, the ecological footprint is a more economical and land-focused way of looking at human impact.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Developed countries tend to have higher ecological footprints, which do not strictly correspond to a country's total population.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] According to research by Dias de Oliveira, Vaughan and Rykiel, "The Ecological Footprint...is an accounting tool based on two fundamental concepts, sustainability and carrying capacity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] One of the major cycles that humans can contribute to that cause a major impact on climate change is the nitrogen cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] This comes from nitrogen fertilizers that humans use.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Gruber and Galloway have researched, "The massive acceleration of the nitrogen cycle caused by the production and industrial use of artificial nitrogen fertilizers worldwide has led to a range of environmental problems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The carbon cycle is another major contributor to climate change primarily from anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A couple examples of how humans contribute to the carbon in the atmosphere is by burning fossil fuels and deforestation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Impact of climate change extend beyond humans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There is a forecast for extinctions of species because of their habitats being affected.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There are major impacts on the marine systems as a result of anthropogenic metabolism, according to Blaustein, the dramatic findings indicate that "every square kilometer [is] affected by some anthropogenic driver of ecological change".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The negative effects of anthropogenic metabolism are seen through the water footprint, ecological footprint, carbon cycle, and the nitrogen cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Studies on the marine ecosystem that show major impacts by humans and developed countries which include more industries, thus more anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] The **anthroposphere** refers to that part of the Earth system that is inhabited and influenced by humans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] The term has been included as one of the Earth's spheres, building on a concept coined by Austrian geologist Eduard Suess.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] While the biosphere is the total biomass of the Earth and its interaction with its systems, the anthroposphere includes the total mass of human-generated systems and materials, including the human population, crops and livestock, and its interaction with the Earth's systems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] A recent study estimated the mass of nonliving anthropogenic creations as 1.1 trillion tons in 2020, equivalent to the mass of all living organisms that comprise the biosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] As human technology has become more evolved, such as that required to launch objects into orbit or to cause deforestation, the impact of human activities on the environment has increased.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] The anthroposphere is the youngest of all the Earth's spheres, yet has made an enormous impact on the Earth and its systems in a very short time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] Some consider the term anthroposphere to be synonymous with the noosphere, though the noosphere is often used to refer specifically to the sphere of rational human thought, or ‘the terrestrial sphere of thinking substance’.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] The anthroposphere is also closely related to the concept of the technosphere developed by geologist Peter Haff, historian of science Jürgen Renn, and others, which refers to all of the technological objects and systems manufactured and created by humans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] The technosphere is distinct from the anthroposphere in these sense that the anthroposphere encompasses not only technologies but cultural, social, economic, and political systems, as well as human behaviors and practices.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] Technofossils are another interesting aspect of the anthroposphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/anthroposphere] These can include objects like mobile phones that contain a diverse range of metals and man-made materials, raw materials like aluminum that do not exist in nature, and agglomerations of plastics created in areas like the Pacific Garbage Patch and on the beaches of the Pacific Islands.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] An **atmosphere** is a layer of gases that envelop an astronomical object, held in place by the gravity of the object.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The name originates from Ancient Greek ἀτμός*(*atmós*)* 'vapour, steam' and σφαῖρα*(*sphaîra*)* 'sphere'.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] An object acquires most of its atmosphere during its primordial epoch, either by accretion of matter or by outgassing of volatiles.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The chemical interaction of the atmosphere with the solid surface can change its fundamental composition, as can photochemical interaction with the Sun.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] A planet retains an atmosphere for longer durations when the gravity is high and the temperature is low.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The solar wind works to strip away a planet's outer atmosphere, although this process is slowed by a magnetosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The further a body is from the Sun, the lower the rate of atmospheric stripping.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Aside from Mercury, all Solar System planets have substantial atmospheres, as does the dwarf planet Pluto and the moon Titan.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The high gravity and low temperature of Jupiter and the other gas giant planets allow them to retain massive atmospheres of mostly hydrogen and helium.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Lower mass terrestrial planets orbit closer to the Sun, and so mainly retain higher molar mass atmospheres made of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, with trace amounts of inert gas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Atmospheres have been detected around exoplanets such as HD 209458 b and Kepler-7b.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] A stellar atmosphere is the outer region of a star, which includes the layers above the opaque photosphere; stars of low temperature might have outer atmospheres containing compound molecules.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Other objects with atmospheres are brown dwarfs and active comets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In the nebular hypothesis, stars form during the gravitational collapse of a mass of gas and dust within an interstellar molecular cloud.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This material forms a pancake-like rotating disk with the mass concentrated at the center.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The protostar is created at the central mass concentration, while the planets and satellites are formed in the disk through a process of accretion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Dust settles into the median disk plane, forming materials that can collide and accrete to create planetesimals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Close to the star, these bodies grow and accumulate to form protoplanets consisting primarily of refractory materials with few volatiles.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Further from the star, planetary embryos are created from accumulation of volatiles up to around ten times the mass of the Earth or more.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Masses of gas are then acquired from the surrounding disk nebula, forming a gas giant around the embryo.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Planetary satellites form in a similar fashion from the disk of material around the planets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The primary atmosphere of a planet is produced when the gravity is sufficient to retain accreted gas against escape processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The latter can include collisions with other bodies that impart sufficient energy for the gasses to escape.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For the terrestrial planets, the high temperatures generated by their initial bombardment results in the outgassing of volatiles, creating the secondary atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The original composition and thickness of the atmosphere is thus determined by the stellar nebula's chemistry and temperature, but can be modified by processes within the astronomical body that release different atmospheric components.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The circumstellar disk will finally dissipate on time scales of about 107 years, and the star will complete its contraction then ignite hydrogen fusion at its core in a time frame determined by its mass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The atmospheres of the planets Venus and Mars are principally composed of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and argon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Because Venus has no oceans or rain to dissolve the carbon dioxide, large amounts of this greenhouse gas has remained in the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The result is a dense atmosphere about 80 times the pressure of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The planet's lack of a magnetic field and closer proximity to the Sun resulted in the loss of its hydrogen (in the form of water) after two billion years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Because Mars is small, cold, and lacks a magnetic field, it has retained only a sparse atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The surface air pressure of 0.6 kPa for Mars is only 0.6% of Earth's 101.3 kPa.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The planet has probably lost at least 80–85% of its original water supply to space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] However, the planet has retained significant deposits of frozen water and carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] If all of the frozen CO2 were to sublimate, the air pressure could climb to 30 kPa.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This is comparable to the air pressure on the top of Mount Everest.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The composition of Earth's atmosphere is determined by the by-products of the life that it sustains.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Dry air (mixture of gases) from Earth's atmosphere contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and traces of hydrogen, helium, and other "noble" gases (by volume), but generally a variable amount of water vapor is also present, on average about 1% at sea level.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Earth's persistent magnetosphere acts as a shield against atmospheric scavenging by the solar wind, as it fends off the incoming plasma at a distance of about 10 Earth radii.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The low temperatures and higher escape velocities of the Solar System's giant planets—Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune—allow them more readily to retain gases with low molecular masses.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These planets have reducing atmospheres of hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of other elements and more complex compounds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Unlike the terrestrial planets, the gas giants lack a well-defined surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Instead the atmosphere is maintained in hydrostatic equilibrium by intense pressure deep in the body.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The dynamic weather on these bodies only occurs in a relatively thin surface layer.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Two satellites of the outer planets possess significant atmospheres.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Titan, a moon of Saturn, and Triton, a moon of Neptune, have atmospheres mainly of nitrogen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] When in the part of its orbit closest to the Sun, Pluto has an atmosphere of nitrogen and methane similar to Triton's, but these gases are frozen when it is farther from the Sun.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Other bodies within the Solar System have extremely thin atmospheres not in equilibrium.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These include the Moon (sodium gas, noble gases, hydrogen), Mercury (sodium gas), Callisto (carbon dioxide and oxygen), Europa (oxygen), Io (sulfur dioxide), and Enceladus (water vapor).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Planetary objects around distant stars, known as exoplanets, span a more diverse range of physical properties than is found in the Solar System.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These targets provide an opportunity to study atmospheres around a broad span of objects and conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] However, observations of these targets requires much more sensitive instrumentation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The methods used to analyze these remote atmospheres are transit spectroscopy, high-resolution Doppler spectroscopy, and direct imaging.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Transit spectroscopy uses the transit of an exoplanet across its host star to detect its atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] By comparing the radius at different wavelengths, the presence of specific components can be detected.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The first such detection was in 2002, when sodium was detected in the atmosphere of HD 209458b, a gas giant with a close orbit around a star in the constellation Pegasus.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Its atmosphere is heated to temperatures over 1,000 K, and is steadily escaping into space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon have been detected in the planet's inflated atmosphere by Hubble observations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Since 2002, potassium has been detected in the atmosphere of XO-2Nb, and both sodium and potassium in HD 189733 b's atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Many of the discovered super earths have orbits close enough to their host star that their surfaces are expected to be magma oceans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The secondary atmospheres of these lava planets most likely consist of materials that have been vaporized from the magma, such as sodium, potassium, oxygen, and silicon oxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] An atmosphere in hydrostatic equilibrium consists of a balance between the air pressure created by the motions of the molecules, and the restraining force of gravity that prevents the molecules from escaping.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The pressure decreases in altitude, producing a pressure-gradient force.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Atmospheric pressure is the force (per unit-area) perpendicular to a unit-area of planetary surface, as determined by the weight of the vertical column of atmospheric gases.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In said atmospheric model, the atmospheric pressure, the weight of the mass of the gas, decreases at high altitude because of the diminishing mass of the gas above the point of barometric measurement.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Air pressure varies by place and time due to meteorological conditions and atmospheric waves.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Units of air pressure are based upon the standard atmosphere (atm), which is 101,325 Pa (equivalent to 760 Torr or 14.696 psi).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For an ideal gas atmosphere, the height at which the atmospheric pressure declines by a factor of *e* (the base of the natural logarithm) is called the scale height (*H*).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For an atmosphere of uniform temperature, the scale height is proportional to the atmospheric temperature and is inversely proportional to the product of the mean molecular mass of dry air, and the local acceleration of gravity at the point of barometric measurement.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The temperature of the atmosphere is determined by an energy budget, which balances the heating from the incoming solar energy against the heat radiated back into space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The incoming energy is determined by the distance from the Sun, and the energy reflected back out by the planetary albedo.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] When a planet is in radiative equilibrium, it has a planetary equilibrium temperature.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This differs from the global mean temperature, which may be warmer than the equilibrium temperature due to the atmospheric greenhouse effect.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For example, Venus has a surface temperature of almost 460 C compared to an equilibrium temperature of −40 C.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Planetary atmospheres are composed of layers with different properties, such as specific gaseous composition, temperature gradients, and pressure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For Earth, Mars, and Venus, the lowest level of the atmosphere is the troposphere, where most of the planet's clouds and weather are found.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This extends from the ground up to 65 km on Venus, 40 km on Mars, and 17 km on Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The troposphere contains the bulk of the atmosphere, possessing 80%–98% of the total atmospheric mass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Temperature varies by altitude according to the lapse rate, as thermal energy from the ground is transported upward via convection.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Infrared radiation becomes trapped by molecules of gas and water vapor.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For the Earth, the next layer is the stratosphere, which is a region of temperature increasing with altitude, creating a temperature inversion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This region contains the UV-absorbing ozone layer, at an altitude between 15 km and 35 km, which is responsible for the temperature rise.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Energy transport in this region occurs through radiation processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Lacking an oxygenated atmosphere to generate a significant layer of ozone, neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Above the troposphere-stratosphere, the next layer of the atmosphere is termed the mesosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In this region, the water vapor and carbon dioxide serves as a heat sink that radiates energy in the infrared.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] As a result, the temperature of the mesosphere decreases with altitude, reaching the coldest layer of the atmosphere at the top.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Both Venus and Mars have an altitude range in the mesosphere where the temperature is nearly isothermal; for Mars this is above 120 km, while for Venus it is between 63 and 75 km altitude.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In the lower regions of the atmosphere, turbulent mixing causes the atmospheric constituents to be evenly distributed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Above a transition layer called the homopause, molecular diffusion dominates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This results in diffuse separation of the constituents by atomic weight; that is, lower mass components diffuse upward leaving higher mass molecules near the bottom.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The homopause is at an altitude of 100–110 km for the Earth, 115–130 km for Mars, and 135–150 km for Venus.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Beyond the mesosphere is a region of the atmosphere called the thermosphere that absorbs X-rays and extreme UV from the Sun, causing temperature to rise with altitude.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The thermal properties of this layer vary daily and with solar activity cycles.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The atmospheric region from the ground through the thermosphere is referred to as the barosphere, since the barometric law holds throughout.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The outermost layer of a planetary atmosphere is termed the exosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Here, the air pressure is so low at this altitude that the distance travelled between molecule collisions, the mean free path, is greater than the atmospheric scale height.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In this region, lower mass components with a thermal velocity exceeding the escape velocity can escape into space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For the Earth, the exosphere is at an altitude of 500 km, while it is around 210 km for Venus and Mars.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] On Earth, the exosphere extends to roughly 10,000 km, where it interacts with the magnetosphere of Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] All three planets have an ionosphere, which is an ionized region of the upper atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The ionospheres for Mars and Venus are closer to the surface and are less dense than on the Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The density of the Earth's ionosphere is greater at short distances from the planetary surface in the daytime and decreases as the ionosphere rises at night-time, thereby allowing a greater range of radio frequencies to travel greater distances.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Gas giants are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium with traces of other elements, giving the planets a low bulk density.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Many of the molecules observed in the outer atmosphere are hydrides, and most of these (with the exception of H2O and H2S) are photochemically destroyed by solar UV in the stratosphere of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These compounds get re-created by thermo-chemical reactions within the hotter, lower regions of the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Complex organic compounds are recycled back to methane by the highly reducing atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The high gravity of these planets combined with their distance from the Sun means that mass loss from their exospheres is negligible, so they form closed systems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] A common feature of the gas giant planets are cloud layers that form where the combination of temperature and pressure are appropriate for condensing a particular volatile.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For Jupiter and Saturn, the outermost cloud layer consists of ice particles of ammonia (NH3), with an underlying layer of ammonium hydrosulfide (NH4SH), then a deep layer of water clouds (H2O).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, the top layer is a methane (CH4) layer of ice particles, followed by the same cloud layers as Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] One difference for Uranus and Neptune is that hydrogen sulfide (H2S) mixes at the same level as the condensed ammonia.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These cloud layers are optically thick, absorbing light at all wavelengths.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The result is a shallower scale height for the outer atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] All four gas giants experience lightning activity in the water clouds, and this is generally much more powerful than terrestrial lightning.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Lightning has been observed on Jupiter, but has not been optically detected on Saturn, Uranus, or Neptune most likely because of their depth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] All of the gas giants have internal heat sources and radiate more heat than they receive from the Sun.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Models for the interiors of Jupiter and Saturn suggest that at a certain depth the hydrogen undergoes a phase change to a metallic hydrogen fluid mixed with ice.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] There is possibly a diffuse or solid core of more massive elements.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, there is no metallic hydrogen; instead there are interior layers of ice, placing these worlds in the sub-category of ice giants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] At sufficient depth, the ice may transition to a supercritical fluid.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Within the Solar System, gas giant planets formed beyond the frost line, where the temperature from the young Sun was low enough for volatiles to condense into solid grains.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In some star systems, dynamic processes in the protoplanetary disk can cause a gas giant to migrate much closer to the central star, creating a hot Jupiter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Through gravitational interaction, the orbit of the planet becomes circularized and it is tidally locked into a synchronous rotation with one side constantly facing the star.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The heated side becomes swollen, and high velocity winds distribute the thermal energy around the planet.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The atmosphere may eventually be stripped away by the star's gravity, leaving behind a super Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] At the upper mass extreme of gas giants is a class of objects known as brown dwarfs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] There is no universal consensus on how to distinguish a brown dwarf from a gas giant, although a commonly used criteria is the ability to fuse deuterium at around 13 times the mass of Jupiter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Once the initial deuterium burning phase of a brown dwarf is concluded, the internal store of heat gradually makes its way to the surface then is radiated away over time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Convection occurs around the core, and possibly at the surface if the brown dwarf is receiving energy from a nearby star.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Radiative energy transfer occurs throughout the remainder of the brown dwarf.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Chemistry can occur throughout the atmosphere, which, depending on the chemical species, can change the opacity to radiative energy transfer.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] As with gas giants, in the cooler outer regions of a brown dwarf, some molecules can condense to form clouds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The circulation of the atmosphere occurs due to thermal differences when convection becomes a more efficient transporter of heat than thermal radiation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] On planets where the primary heat source is solar radiation, excess heat in the tropics is transported to higher latitudes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] When a planet generates a significant amount of heat internally, such as is the case for Jupiter, convection in the atmosphere can transport thermal energy from the higher temperature interior up to the surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The thermally-driven meridional circulation of Earth, Mars, and Venus are dominated by the Hadley cell.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This is created by rising air in the warmest region of the planet accompanied by descending air where it is cooler.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] However, there are significant differences in the circulation patterns between the three planets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For Venus, the lower atmosphere of Venus has two symmetrical equator to near pole circulation cells, with a higher altitude sub-solar to anti-solar circulation cell.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] On Earth, Hadley cells exist on each side of the equator, but these vary seasonally due to the planet's obliquity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Mars is similar to the Earth in this respect, but it displays greater seasonality due to its thinner atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] It has two Hadley cells during equinox, but a single cell at solstice.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The Earth has multiple counter-rotating convection cells, with the Hadley cell on either side of the equator, an intermediate Ferrel cell along the mid-latitudes, and polar cells at each pole.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The planet's rotation induces a Coriolis force that creates a curvature in the north-south convection flow.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] As air moves toward a pole, the latitudinal flow remains steady but the distance needed to encircle the planet grows shorter, creating a curved path along the surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These flows create the prevailing winds along the planet's surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Near the equator, the air flow creates the trade winds which flow from east to west.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] At the mid-latitudes, the westerlies brings the air flow from the west in the United States and Europe.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Finally, the polar easterlies moves polar air from east to west.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Both Jupiter and Saturn display banded cloud formations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These are associated with alternating jets known as zonal flows that follow latitudinal lines.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The bands alternate in direction, with the equatorial jet moving eastward at 150 km/s on Jupiter and 300 km/s on Saturn.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] It remains unclear whether these flows occur in the shallow layers around the clouds, or extend much deeper into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Observations of Neptune show a similar zonal flow structure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] This planet displays the largest range of differential rotation in the Solar System.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Surface gravity differs significantly among the planets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For example, the large gravitational force of the giant planet Jupiter retains light gases such as hydrogen and helium that escape from objects with lower gravity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Secondly, the distance from the Sun determines the energy available to heat atmospheric gas to the point where some fraction of its molecules' thermal motion exceed the planet's escape velocity, allowing those to escape a planet's gravitational grasp.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Thus, distant and cold Titan, Triton, and Pluto are able to retain components of their original atmospheres despite their relatively low gravities.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Since a collection of gas molecules may be moving at a wide range of velocities, there will always be some fast enough to produce a slow leakage of gas into space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Lighter molecules move faster than heavier ones with the same thermal kinetic energy, and so gases of low molecular weight are lost more rapidly than those of high molecular weight.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] It is thought that Venus and Mars may have lost much of their water when, after being photodissociated into hydrogen and oxygen by solar ultraviolet radiation, the hydrogen escaped.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Earth's magnetic field helps to prevent this, as, normally, the solar wind would greatly enhance the escape of hydrogen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] However, over the past 3 billion years Earth may have lost gases through the magnetic polar regions due to auroral activity, including a net 2% of its atmospheric oxygen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The net effect, taking the most important escape processes into account, is that an intrinsic magnetic field does not protect a planet from atmospheric escape and that for some magnetizations the presence of a magnetic field works to increase the escape rate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Planets around small M-type main-sequence stars may be particularly prone to atmospheric loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The star will spend an extended period as a superluminous pre-main-sequence star, then experience high levels of activity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The strong stellar magnetic field will tend to reduce the size of planetary magnetospheres, leading to greater erosion from the stellar wind.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Planets around older M-type stars may become tidally locked in synchronous orbit, leading to the atmosphere being permanently frozen on the dark face.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Other mechanisms that can cause atmosphere depletion are solar wind-induced sputtering, impact erosion, weathering, and sequestration—sometimes referred to as "freezing out"—into the regolith and polar caps.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] An extreme example of the latter is a comet, which is a small body that forms beyond the frost line in the protoplanetary disk.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These objects contain many types of frozen volatiles, including water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, methane, and formaldehyde.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] As these objects approach the Sun, the thermal radiation causes the volatiles to sublimate, creating a diffuse, dusty atmosphere around the comet; the coma.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] However, the gravitational potential of the comet is insufficient to retain this atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] The Solar System contains a large number of bodies that are now practically airless, such as Mercury and the Moon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] These objects have only an exosphere layer with particles that are essentially collisionless.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In this environment, atoms and molecules are released from the surface by various means, including particle sputtering and micrometeorite impact.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] When the release velocity of these particles exceed the escape velocity, they are lost to space.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Higher mass particles have a greater chance to be returned to the surface, which creates a chemical alteration of the surface over time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] On a terrestrial planet, the part of the atmosphere that directly interacts with the ground is known as the planetary boundary layer.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Atmospheres have dramatic effects on the surfaces of rocky bodies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Wind erosion is a significant factor in shaping the terrain of rocky planets with atmospheres, and over time can erase the effects of both craters and volcanoes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In addition, since liquids cannot exist without pressure, an atmosphere allows liquid to be present at the surface, resulting in lakes, rivers and oceans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Earth and Titan are known to have liquids at their surface and terrain on the planet Mars suggests that it had liquid on its surface in the past.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Objects that have no atmosphere, or that have only an exosphere, have terrain that is covered in craters.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Without an atmosphere, the planet has no protection from meteoroids, and all of them collide with the surface as meteorites and create craters.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For planets with a significant atmosphere, most meteoroids burn up as meteors before hitting a planet's surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] When meteoroids do impact, the effects are often erased by the action of wind.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] From the perspective of a planetary geologist, the atmosphere acts to shape a planetary surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Wind picks up dust and other particles which, when they collide with the terrain, erode the relief and leave deposits (eolian processes).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Frost and precipitations, which depend on the atmospheric composition, also influence the relief.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Climate changes can influence a planet's geological history.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] Conversely, studying the surface of the Earth leads to an understanding of the atmosphere and climate of other planets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For a meteorologist, the composition of the Earth's atmosphere is a factor affecting the climate and its variations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] For a biologist or paleontologist, the Earth's atmospheric composition is closely dependent on the appearance of life and its evolution.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/atmosphere] In astrobiology, the composition of an exoplanet's atmosphere is closely intertwined with the possibility of extraterrestrial life.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many scientists, along with the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services*, say that the main reason for biodiversity loss is a growing human population because this leads to human overpopulation and excessive consumption.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Others disagree, saying that loss of habitat is caused mainly by "the growth of commodities for export" and that population has very little to do with overall consumption.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] More important are wealth disparities between and within countries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In any case, all contemporary biodiversity loss has been attributed to human activities.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Climate change is another threat to global biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, coral reefs—which are biodiversity hotspots—will be lost by the year 2100 if global warming continues at the current rate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, the change of temperatures are likely to increase fire activity driving events such as forest fires.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Still, it is the general habitat destruction (often for expansion of agriculture), not climate change, that is currently the bigger driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Invasive species and other disturbances have become more common in forests in the last several decades.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and can cause a deterioration of forest ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Groups that care about the environment have been working for many years to stop the decrease in biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Nowadays, many global policies include activities to stop biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, the UN Convention on Biological Diversity aims to prevent biodiversity loss and to conserve wilderness areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] However, a 2020 United Nations Environment Programme report found that most of these efforts had failed to meet their goals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, of the 20 biodiversity goals laid out by the Aichi Biodiversity Targets in 2010, only six were "partially achieved" by 2020.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The current rate of global biodiversity loss is estimated to be 100 to 1000 times higher than the (naturally occurring) background extinction rate, faster than at any other time in human history, and is expected to grow in the upcoming years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The fast-growing extinction trends of various animal groups like mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish have led scientists to declare a current biodiversity crisis in both land and ocean ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2006, many more species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk that have not been formally recognized.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There is also evidence showing that species which are not formally recognized are at greater risk of extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Deforestation also plays a large role in biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] More than half of the world's biodiversity is hosted in tropical rainforest.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Regions that are subjected to exponential loss of biodiversity are referred to as biodiversity hotspots.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Since 1988 the hotspots increased from 10 to 34.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Of the total 34 hotspots currently present, 16 of them are in tropical regions (as of 2006).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Researchers have noted in 2006 that only 2.3% of the world is covered with biodiversity loss hotspots, and even though only a small percentage of the world is covered in hotspots, it host a large fraction (50%) of vascular plant species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2021, about 28 percent of the 134,400 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 37,400 species compared to 16,119 threatened species in 2006.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Research published in 2023 found that, out of 70,000 species, about 48% are facing decreasing populations due to human activities, while only 3% are seeing an increase in populations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Biologists define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] To measure biodiversity loss rates for a particular location, scientists record the species richness and its variation over time in that area.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In ecology, local abundance is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is called relative species abundance.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There are many different biodiversity indexes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These investigate different scales and time spans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Biodiversity has various scales and subcategories (e.g. phylogenetic diversity, species diversity, genetic diversity, nucleotide diversity).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The question of *net loss* in confined regions is often a matter of debate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] An October 2020 analysis by Swiss Re found that one-fifth of all countries are at risk of ecosystem collapse as the result of anthropogenic habitat destruction and increased wildlife loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] If these losses are not reversed, a total ecosystem collapse could ensue.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, the World Wildlife Fund reported an average population decline of 68% between 1970 and 2016 for 4,400 animal species worldwide, encompassing nearly 21,000 monitored populations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Insects are the most numerous and widespread class in the animal kingdom, accounting for up to 90% of all animal species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In the 2010s, reports emerged about the widespread decline in populations across multiple insect orders.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The reported severity shocked many observers, even though there had been earlier findings of pollinator decline.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There have also been anecdotal reports of greater insect abundance earlier in the 20th century.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many car drivers know this anecdotal evidence through the windscreen phenomenon, for example.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Causes for the decline in insect population are similar to those driving other biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] They include habitat destruction, such as intensive agriculture, the use of pesticides (particularly insecticides), introduced species, and the effects of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] An additional cause that may be specific to insects is light pollution (research in that area is ongoing).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Most commonly, the declines involve reductions in abundance, though in some cases entire species are going extinct.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In some localities, there have been reports of increases in overall insect population, and some types of insects appear to be increasing in abundance across the world.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Not all insect orders are affected in the same way; most affected are bees, butterflies, moths, beetles, dragonflies and damselflies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many of the remaining insect groups have received less research to date.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Also, comparative figures from earlier decades are often not available.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In the few major global studies, estimates of the total number of insect species at risk of extinction range between 10% and 40%, though all of these estimates have been fraught with controversy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Scientists have studied loss of earthworms from several long-term agronomic trials.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] They found that relative biomass losses of minus 50–100% (with a mean of minus 83%) match or exceed those reported for other faunal groups.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Thus it is clear that earthworms are similarly depleted in the soils of fields used for intensive agriculture.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Earthworms play an important role in ecosystem function, helping with biological processing in soil, water, and even greenhouse gas balancing.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There are five reasons for the decline of earthworm diversity: "(1) soil degradation and habitat loss, (2) climate change, (3) excessive nutrient and other forms of contamination load, (4) over-exploitation and unsustainable management of soil, and (5) invasive species".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Factors like tillage practices and intensive land use decimate the soil and plant roots that earthworms use to create their biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This interferes with carbon and nitrogen cycles.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Knowledge of earthworm species diversity is quite limited as not even 50% of them have been described.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Sustainable agriculture methods could help prevent earthworm diversity decline, for example reduced tillage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The Secretariat of the Convention on Biological Diversity is trying to take action and promote the restoration and maintenance of the many diverse species of earthworms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Since the 1980s, decreases in amphibian populations, including population decline and localized mass extinctions, have been observed in locations all over the world.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This type of biodiversity loss is known as one of the most critical threats to global biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The possible causes include habitat destruction and modification, diseases, exploitation, pollution, pesticide use, introduced species, and ultraviolet-B radiation (UV-B).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] However, many of the causes of amphibian declines are still poorly understood, and the topic is currently a subject of ongoing research.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Modeling results found that the current extinction rate of amphibians could be 211 times greater than the background extinction rate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This estimate even goes up to 25,000–45,000 times if endangered species are also included in the computation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The decline of wild mammal populations globally has been an occurrence spanning over the past 50,000 years, at the same time as the populations of humans and livestock have increased.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Nowadays, the total biomass of wild mammals on land is believed to be seven times lower than its prehistoric values, while the biomass of marine mammals had declined fivefold.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] At the same time, the biomass of humans is "an order of magnitude higher than that of all wild mammals", and the biomass of livestock mammals like pigs and cattle is even larger than that.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Even as wild mammals had declined, the growth in the numbers of humans and livestock had increased total mammal biomass fourfold.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Only 4% of that increased number are wild mammals, while livestock and humans amount to 60% and 36%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Alongside the simultaneous halving of plant biomass, these striking declines are considered part of the prehistoric phase of the Holocene extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Since the second half of the 20th century, a range of protected areas and other wildlife conservation efforts (such as the Repopulation of wolves in Midwestern United States) have been implemented.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These have had some impact on preserving wild mammal numbers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There is still some debate over the total extent of recent declines in wild mammals and other vertebrate species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In any case, many species are now in a worse state than decades ago.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Hundreds of species are critically endangered.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Climate change also has negative impacts on land mammal populations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Some pesticides, like insecticides, likely play a role in reducing the populations of specific bird species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] According to a study funded by BirdLife International, 51 bird species are critically endangered and eight could be classified as extinct or in danger of extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Nearly 30% of extinction is due to hunting and trapping for the exotic pet trade.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Deforestation, caused by unsustainable logging and agriculture, could be the next extinction driver, because birds lose their habitat and their food.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] While plants are essential for human survival, they have not received the same attention as the conservation of animals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It is estimated that a third of all land plant species are at risk of extinction and 94% have yet to be evaluated in terms of their conservation status.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Plants existing at the lowest trophic level require increased conservation to reduce negative impacts at higher trophic levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, scientists warned that a third of tree species are threatened with extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This will significantly alter the world's ecosystems because their plant responses, carbon, water and nutrient cycles will be affected.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Forest areas are degraded due to common factors such as logging, fire, and firewood harvesting.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Especially with forest fires and its increases, it will affect biomass recovery and affect species composition as well.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The Global Tree Assessment (GTA) has determined that "17,510 (29.9%) tree species are considered threatened with extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Possible solutions can be found in some silvicultural methods of forest management that promote tree biodiversity, such as selective logging, thinning or crop tree management, and clear cutting and coppicing.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Without solutions, secondary forests recovery in species richness can take 50 years to recover the same amount as the primary forest, or 20 years to recover 80% of species richness.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Human impact on the environment has driven a range of species extinct and is threatening even more today.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Multiple organizations such as IUCN and Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew suggest that around 40% of plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The majority are threatened by habitat loss, but activities such as logging of wild timber trees and collection of medicinal plants, or the introduction of non-native invasive species, also play a role.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Relatively few plant diversity assessments have considered climate change, yet it is starting to impact plants as well.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] About 3% of flowering plants are very likely to be driven extinct within a century at 2 °C (3.6 °F) of global warming, and 10% at 3.2 °C (5.8 °F).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In worst-case scenarios, half of all tree species may be driven extinct by climate change over that timeframe.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Freshwater ecosystems such as swamps, deltas, and rivers make up 1% of earth's surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] They are important because they are home to approximately one third of vertebrate species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Freshwater species are beginning to decline at twice the rate of species that live on land or in the ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This rapid loss has already placed 27% of 29,500 species dependent on fresh water on the IUCN Red List.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Global populations of freshwater fish are collapsing due to water pollution and overfishing.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Migratory fish populations have declined by 76% since 1970, and large "megafish" populations have fallen by 94% with 16 species declared extinct in 2020.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Marine biodiversity encompasses any living organism that resides in the ocean or in estuaries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] By 2018, approximately 240,000 marine species had been documented.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] But many marine species—estimates range between 178,000 and 10 million oceanic species—remain to be described.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It is therefore likely that a number of rare species (not seen for decades in the wild) have already disappeared or are on the brink of extinction, unnoticed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Human activities have a strong and detrimental influence on marine biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The main drivers of marine species extinction are habitat loss, pollution, invasive species, and overexploitation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Greater pressure is placed on marine ecosystems near coastal areas because of the human settlements in those areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Overexploitation has resulted in the extinction of over 25 marine species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This includes seabirds, marine mammals, algae, and fish.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Examples of extinct marine species include Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) and the Caribbean monk seal (*Monachus tropicalis*).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Not all extinctions are because of humans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, in the 1930s, the eelgrass limpet (*Lottia alveus*) became extinct in the Atlantic once the *Zostera marina* seagrass population declined upon exposure to a disease.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The *Lottia alveus* were greatly impacted because the *Zostera marina* were their sole habitats.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Jared Diamond describes an "Evil Quartet" of habitat destruction, overkill, introduced species and secondary extinctions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Wilson suggested the acronym HIPPO for the main causes of biodiversity loss: **H**abitat destruction, **I**nvasive species, **P**ollution, human over-**P**opulation and **O**ver-harvesting.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Habitat destruction (also termed habitat loss) occurs when a natural habitat is no longer able to support its native species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The organisms once living there have either moved elsewhere, or are dead, leading to a decrease in biodiversity and species numbers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Habitat destruction is in fact the leading cause of biodiversity loss and species extinction worldwide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Humans contribute to habitat destruction through the use of natural resources, agriculture, industrial production and urbanization (urban sprawl).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Other activities include mining, logging, and trawling.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Environmental factors can contribute to habitat destruction more indirectly.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Geological processes, climate change, introduction of invasive species, ecosystem nutrient depletion, water and noise pollution are some of the examples.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Loss of habitat can be preceded by an initial habitat fragmentation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Fragmentation and loss of habitat have become one of the most important topics of research in ecology as they are major threats to the survival of endangered species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, habitat loss is one of the causes in the decline of insect populations (see the section below on insects).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The direct effects of urban growth on habitat loss are well understood: building construction often results in habitat destruction and fragmentation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This leads to selection for species that are adapted to urban environments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Small habitat patches cannot support the level of genetic or taxonomic diversity they formerly could while some more sensitive species may become locally extinct.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Species abundance populations are reduced due to the reduced fragmented area of habitat.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This causes an increase of species isolation and forces species toward edge habitats and to adapt to foraging elsewhere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, edge effects often result in altered light, temperature, and humidity conditions that change vegetation structure and microhabitat suitability, further reducing biodiversity in fragmented urban patches.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Urban environments also favor fast-reproducing, mobile species, contributing to biotic homogenization and the global decline of ecological uniqueness.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure development in Key Biodiversity Areas (KBA) is a major driver of biodiversity loss, with infrastructure present in roughly 80% of KBAs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure development leads to conversion and fragmentation of natural habitat, pollution and disturbance.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There can also be direct harm to animals through collisions with vehicles and structures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This can have impacts beyond the infrastructure site.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, chronic noise from roads can interfere with bird song used in mating and territory defense, reducing reproductive success.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Artificial lighting can disrupt nocturnal foraging patterns, predator-prey interactions, and migratory navigation in species such as bats, amphibians, and sea turtles.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure can also create ecological traps, where animals are drawn to altered environments that ultimately reduce their fitness or survival.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Furthermore, road mortality and bird collisions with buildings and power lines cause direct harm to wildlife, with cascading impacts across trophic levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These impacts often extend well beyond the development footprint and may disrupt landscape connectivity critical for migration and climate adaptation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Fragmented landscapes also impede species' range shifts in response to climate change, making it harder for populations to track suitable environmental conditions and increasing extinction risk.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Humans are changing the uses of land in various ways, and each can lead to habitat destruction and biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The 2019 *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* found that industrial agriculture is the primary driver of biodiversity collapse.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] According to a 2005 publication, "Cultivated systems [...] cover 24% of Earth's surface".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] More than 17,000 species are at risk of losing habitat by 2050 as agriculture continues to expand to meet future food needs (as of 2020).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A global shift toward largely plant-based diets would free up land to allow for the restoration of ecosystems and biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In the 2010s over 80% of all global farmland was used to rear animals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Recent FAO data shows that livestock systems occupy about 77% of agricultural land while providing less than 20% of the global calorie supply — highlighting an imbalance between land use and nutritional output.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] As of 2022, 44% of Earth's land area required conservation attention, which may include declaring protected areas and following land-use policies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, a 2023 analysis in *Science Advances* concluded that at least 30% of land must be actively protected and ecologically restored by 2030 to meet global biodiversity goals, aligning with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework agreed upon at COP15.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Air pollution adversely affects biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Pollutants are emitted into the atmosphere by the burning of fossil fuels and biomass, for example.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Industrial and agricultural activity releases the pollutants sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Once sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide are introduced into the atmosphere, they can react with cloud droplets (cloud condensation nuclei), raindrops, or snowflakes, forming sulfuric acid and nitric acid.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] With the interaction between water droplets and sulfuric and nitric acids, wet deposition occurs and creates acid rain.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A 2009 review studied four air pollutants (sulfur, nitrogen, ozone, and mercury) and several types of ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Air pollution affects the functioning and biodiversity of terrestrial as well as aquatic ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, "air pollution causes or contributes to acidification of lakes, eutrophication of estuaries and coastal waters, and mercury bioaccumulation in aquatic food webs".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Noise generated by traffic, ships, vehicles, and aircraft can affect the survivability of wildlife species and can reach undisturbed habitats.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution is common in marine ecosystems, affecting at least 55 marine species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] One study found that as seismic noises and naval sonar increases in marine ecosystems, cetacean diversity decreases (including whales and dolphins).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Multiple studies have found that fewer fishes, such as cod, haddock, rockfish, herring, sand seal, and blue whiting, have been spotted in areas with seismic noises, with catch rates declining by 40–80%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution has also altered avian communities and diversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Noise can reduce reproductive success, minimize nesting areas, increase stress response, and reduce species abundance.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution can alter the distribution and abundance of prey species, which can then impact predator populations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Fossil fuel extraction and associated oil and gas pipelines have major impacts on the biodiversity of many biomes due to land conversion, habitat loss and degradation, and pollution.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] An example is the Western Amazon region.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Exploitation of fossil fuels there has had significant impacts on biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] As of 2018, many of the protected areas with rich biodiversity were in areas containing unexploited fossil fuel reserves worth between $3 and $15 trillion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The protected areas may be under threat in future.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Continued overexploitation can lead to the destruction of the resource, as it will be unable to replenish.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The term applies to natural resources such as water aquifers, grazing pastures and forests, wild medicinal plants, fish stocks and other wildlife.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A 2019 Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services report found that overfishing is the main driver of mass species extinction in oceans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Overfishing has reduced fish and marine mammal biomass by 60% since the 1800s.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It is currently pushing over one-third of sharks and rays toward extinction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many commercial fishes have been overharvested: a 2020 FAO report classified as overfished 34% of the fish stocks of the world's marine fisheries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] By 2020, global fish populations had declined 38% since 1970.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many regulatory measures are available for controlling overfishing.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These include fishing quotas, bag limits, licensing, closed seasons, size limits, and the creation of marine reserves and other marine protected areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The world's population numbered nearly 7.6 billion as of mid-2017 and is forecast to peak toward the end of the 21st century at 10–12 billion people.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Scholars have argued that population size and growth, along with overconsumption, are significant factors in biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Review articles, including the 2019 IPBES report, have also noted that human population growth and overconsumption are significant drivers of species decline.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A 2022 study warned that conservation efforts will continue to fail if the primary drivers of biodiversity loss continue to be ignored, including population size and growth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Other scientists have criticized the assertion that population growth is a key driver for biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] On the other hand, the correlation between a country's GDP and its footprint is strong.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The study argues that population as a metric is unhelpful and counterproductive for tackling environmental challenges.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The term *invasive* is poorly defined and often very subjective.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The European Union defines *invasive alien species* as those outside their natural distribution area that threaten biological diversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Biotic invasion is considered one of the five top drivers of global biodiversity loss and is increasing because of tourism and globalization.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This may be particularly true in poorly regulated fresh water systems, though quarantines and ballast water rules have improved the situation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Invasive species may drive local native species to extinction via competitive exclusion, niche displacement, or hybridisation with related native species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Therefore, alien invasions may result in extensive changes in the structure, composition and global distribution of the biota at sites of introduction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This leads to the homogenisation of the world's fauna and flora and biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It has changed rapidly due to human activities, such as burning fossil fuels and release of methane gas and pollution.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Recent studies have found that global surface temperatures are expected to increase due to atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] But habitat destruction, e.g., for the expansion of agriculture, is currently a more significant driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A 2021 collaborative report by scientists from the IPBES and the IPCC found that biodiversity loss and climate change must be addressed simultaneously, as they are inextricably linked and have similar effects on human well-being.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, Frans Timmermans, Vice-President of the European Commission, said that people are less aware of the threat of biodiversity loss than they are of the threat of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The interaction between climate change and invasive species is complex and not easy to assess.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Climate change is likely to favour some invasive species and harm others, but few authors have identified specific consequences of climate change for invasive species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and have negative consequences for forest ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Climate change contributes to destruction of some habitats, endangering various species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There are several plausible pathways that could lead to plant and animal species extinction from climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Every species has evolved to exist within a certain ecological niche, but climate change leads to changes of temperature and average weather patterns.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] These changes can push climatic conditions outside of the species' niche, and ultimately render it extinct.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Normally, species faced with changing conditions can either adapt in place through microevolution or move to another habitat with suitable conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] However, the speed of recent climate change is very fast.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Due to this rapid change, for example cold-blooded animals (a category which includes amphibians, reptiles and all invertebrates) may struggle to find a suitable habitat within 50 km of their current location at the end of this century (for a *mid-range scenario* of future global warming).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Climate change also increases both the frequency and intensity of extreme weather events, which can directly wipe out regional populations of species.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Those species occupying coastal and low-lying island habitats can also become extinct by sea level rise.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This has already happened with Bramble Cay melomys in Australia, which was the first mammal to go extinct due to human-induced sea level rise, with the Australian government officially confirming its extinction in 2019.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Permanent global species loss (extinction) is a more dramatic phenomenon than regional changes in species composition.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] But even minor changes from a healthy stable state can have a dramatic influence on the food web and the food chain, because reductions in one species can adversely affect the entire chain (coextinction).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] This can lead to an overall reduction in biodiversity, unless alternative stable states of the ecosystem are possible.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, a study on grasslands used manipulated grassland plant diversity and found that ecosystems with higher biodiversity show more resistance of their productivity to climate extremes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] To reduce biodiversity loss related to agricultural practices, FAO encourages the use of "biodiversity-friendly management practices in crop and livestock production, forestry, fisheries and aquaculture".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The WHO has analyzed how biodiversity and human health are connected: "Biodiversity and human health, and the respective policies and activities, are interlinked in various ways.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] First, biodiversity gives rise to health benefits.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For example, the variety of species and genotypes provide nutrients and medicines." The ongoing drivers and effects of biodiversity loss has the potential to lead to future zoonotic disease outbreaks like the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Medicinal and aromatic plants are widely used in traditional medicine as well as in cosmetic and food industries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The WHO estimated in 2015 that about "60,000 species are used for their medicinal, nutritional and aromatic properties".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] There is a global trade in plants for medicinal purposes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Biodiversity contributes to the development of pharmaceuticals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] A significant proportion of medicines are derived from natural products, either directly or indirectly.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many of these natural products come from marine ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] However, unregulated and inappropriate over-harvesting (bioprospecting) could potentially lead to overexploitation, ecosystem degradation and loss of biodiversity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Users and traders harvest plants for traditional medicine either by planting them or by collecting them in the wild.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In both cases, sustainable medicinal resource management is important.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Scientists are investigating what can be done to address biodiversity loss and climate change together.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] For both of these crises, there is a need to "conserve enough nature and in the right places".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Additional measures for protecting biodiversity, beyond just environmental protection, are important.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Such measures include addressing drivers of land use change, increasing efficiency in agriculture, and reducing the need for animal agriculture.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The latter could be achieved by increasing the shares of plant-based diets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Many governments have conserved portions of their territories under the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), a multilateral treaty signed in 1992–3.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The 20 Aichi Biodiversity Targets are part of the CBD's *Strategic Plan 2011–2020* and were published in 2010.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Aichi Target Number 11 aimed to protect 17% of terrestrial and inland water areas and 10% of coastal and marine areas by 2020 .
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Of the 20 biodiversity goals laid out by the Aichi Biodiversity Targets in 2010, only six were *partially achieved* by 2020.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The 2020 CBD report highlighted that if the status quo does not change, biodiversity will continue to decline due to "currently unsustainable patterns of production and consumption, population growth and technological developments".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The report also singled out Australia, Brazil, Cameroon and the Galapagos Islands (Ecuador) for having had one of its animals lost to extinction in the previous ten years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Following this, the leaders of 64 nations and the European Union pledged to halt environmental degradation and restore the natural world.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The pledge was not signed by leaders from some of the world's biggest polluters, namely China, India, Russia, Brazil and the United States.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Some experts contend that the United States' refusal to ratify the Convention on Biological Diversity is harming global efforts to halt the extinction crisis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Scientists say that even if the targets for 2020 had been met, no substantial reduction of extinction rates would likely have resulted.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Others have raised concerns that the Convention on Biological Diversity does not go far enough, and argue the goal should be zero extinctions by 2050, along with cutting the impact of unsustainable food production on nature by half.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] That the targets are not legally binding has also been subject to criticism.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In December 2022, every country except the United States and the Holy See signed onto the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework at the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.This framework calls for protecting 30% of land and oceans by 2030 (30 by 30).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] It also has 22 other targets intended to reduce biodiversity loss.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] At the time of signing the agreement, only 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The agreement includes protecting the rights of Indigenous peoples and changing the current subsidy policy to one better for biodiversity protection, but it takes a step backward in protecting species from extinction in comparison to the Aichi Targets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Critics said the agreement does not go far enough to protect biodiversity, and that the process was rushed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] In 2019 the Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES) published the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services.* This report said that up to a million plant and animal species are facing extinction because of human activity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The IPBES is an international organization that has a similar role to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), except that it focuses on biodiversity and ecosystem services, not climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] The United Nations' Sustainable Development Goal 15 (SDG 15), "Life on Land", includes biodiversity targets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Its fifth target is: "Take urgent and significant action to reduce the degradation of natural habitats, halt the loss of biodiversity and, by 2020, protect and prevent the extinction of threatened species." This target has one indicator: the Red List Index.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Nearly three-quarters of bird species, two thirds of mammals and more than half of hard corals have been recorded at World Heritage Sites, even though they cover less than 1% of the planet.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/biodiversity-loss] Countries with World Heritage Sites can include them in their national biodiversity strategies and action plans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The **carbon cycle** is a part of the biogeochemical cycle where carbon is exchanged among the biosphere, pedosphere, geosphere, hydrosphere, and atmosphere of Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Other major biogeochemical cycles include the nitrogen cycle and the water cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon is the main component of biological compounds as well as a major component of many rocks such as limestone.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The carbon cycle comprises a sequence of events that are key to making Earth capable of sustaining life.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It describes the movement of carbon as it is recycled and reused throughout the biosphere, as well as long-term processes of carbon sequestration (storage) to and release from carbon sinks.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] At 422.7 parts per million (ppm), the global average atmospheric carbon dioxide has set a new record high in 2024.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] To describe the dynamics of the carbon cycle, a distinction can be made between the *fast* and *slow* carbon cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The fast cycle is also referred to as the *biological carbon cycle*.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Fast cycles can complete within years, moving substances from atmosphere to biosphere, then back to the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Slow or geological cycles (also called deep carbon cycle) can take millions of years to complete, moving substances through the Earth's crust between rocks, soil, ocean and atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Humans have disturbed the carbon cycle for many centuries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] They have done so by modifying land use and by mining and burning carbon from ancient organic remains (coal, petroleum and gas).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide in the atmosphere has increased nearly 52% over pre-industrial levels by 2020, resulting in global warming.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The increased carbon dioxide has also caused a reduction in the ocean's pH value and is fundamentally altering marine chemistry.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide is critical for photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The carbon cycle was first described by Antoine Lavoisier and Joseph Priestley, and popularised by Humphry Davy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The carbon exchanges between reservoirs occur as the result of various chemical, physical, geological, and biological processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The ocean contains the largest active pool of carbon near the surface of the Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The natural flows of carbon between the atmosphere, ocean, terrestrial ecosystems, and sediments are fairly balanced; so carbon levels would be roughly stable without human influence.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon in the Earth's atmosphere exists in two main forms: carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Both of these gases absorb and retain heat in the atmosphere and are partially responsible for the greenhouse effect.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Methane produces a larger greenhouse effect per volume as compared to carbon dioxide, but it exists in much lower concentrations and is more short-lived than carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Thus, carbon dioxide contributes more to the global greenhouse effect than methane.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere primarily through photosynthesis and enters the terrestrial and oceanic biospheres.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide also dissolves directly from the atmosphere into bodies of water (ocean, lakes, etc.), as well as dissolving in precipitation as raindrops fall through the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] When dissolved in water, carbon dioxide reacts with water molecules and forms carbonic acid, which contributes to ocean acidity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It can then be absorbed by rocks through weathering.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It also can acidify other surfaces it touches or be washed into the ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In the far future (2 to 3 billion years), the rate at which carbon dioxide is absorbed into the soil via the carbonate–silicate cycle will likely increase due to expected changes in the Sun as it ages.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The expected increased luminosity of the Sun will likely speed up the rate of surface weathering.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This will eventually cause most of the carbon dioxide in the atmosphere to be squelched into the Earth's crust as carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Once the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere falls below approximately 50 parts per million (tolerances vary among species), C3 photosynthesis will no longer be possible.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This has been predicted to occur 600 million years from the present, though models vary.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Once the oceans on the Earth evaporate in about 1.1 billion years from now, plate tectonics will very likely stop due to the lack of water to lubricate them.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The lack of volcanoes pumping out carbon dioxide will cause the carbon cycle to end between 1 billion and 2 billion years into the future.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The terrestrial biosphere includes the organic carbon in all land-living organisms, both alive and dead, as well as carbon stored in soils.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] About 500 gigatons of carbon are stored above ground in plants and other living organisms, while soil holds approximately 1,500 gigatons of carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Most carbon in the terrestrial biosphere is organic carbon, while about a third of soil carbon is stored in inorganic forms, such as calcium carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Organic carbon is a major component of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Autotrophs extract it from the air in the form of carbon dioxide, converting it to organic carbon, while heterotrophs receive carbon by consuming other organisms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Because carbon uptake in the terrestrial biosphere is dependent on biotic factors, it follows a diurnal and seasonal cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In CO2 measurements, this feature is apparent in the Keeling curve.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It is strongest in the northern hemisphere because this hemisphere has more land mass than the southern hemisphere and thus more room for ecosystems to absorb and emit carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon leaves the terrestrial biosphere in several ways and on different time scales.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The combustion or respiration of organic carbon releases it rapidly into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It can also be exported into the ocean through rivers or remain sequestered in soils in the form of inert carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon stored in soil can remain there for up to thousands of years before being washed into rivers by erosion or released into the atmosphere through soil respiration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Between 1989 and 2008 soil respiration increased by about 0.1% per year.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] There are a few plausible explanations for this trend, but the most likely explanation is that increasing temperatures have increased rates of decomposition of soil organic matter, which has increased the flow of CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The length of carbon sequestering in soil is dependent on local climatic conditions and thus changes in the course of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The ocean can be conceptually divided into a surface layer within which water makes frequent (daily to annual) contact with the atmosphere, and a deep layer below the typical mixed layer depth of a few hundred meters or less, within which the time between consecutive contacts may be centuries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC) in the surface layer is exchanged rapidly with the atmosphere, maintaining equilibrium.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon enters the ocean mainly through the dissolution of atmospheric carbon dioxide, a small fraction of which is converted into carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It can also enter the ocean through rivers as dissolved organic carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It is converted by organisms into organic carbon through photosynthesis and can either be exchanged throughout the food chain or precipitated into the oceans' deeper, more carbon-rich layers as dead soft tissue or in shells as calcium carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It circulates in this layer for long periods of time before either being deposited as sediment or, eventually, returned to the surface waters through thermohaline circulation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Oceans are basic (with a current pH value of 8.1 to 8.2).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The increase in atmospheric CO2 shifts the pH of the ocean towards neutral in a process called ocean acidification.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Oceanic absorption of CO2 is one of the most important forms of carbon sequestering.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The projected rate of pH reduction could slow the biological precipitation of calcium carbonates, thus decreasing the ocean's capacity to absorb CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The geologic component of the carbon cycle operates slowly in comparison to the other parts of the global carbon cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It is one of the most important determinants of the amount of carbon in the atmosphere, and thus of global temperatures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Most of the Earth's carbon is stored inertly in the Earth's lithosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Much of the carbon stored in the Earth's mantle was stored there when the Earth formed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Some of it was deposited in the form of organic carbon from the biosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Of the carbon stored in the geosphere, about 80% is limestone and its derivatives, which form from the sedimentation of calcium carbonate stored in the shells of marine organisms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The remaining 20% is stored as kerogens formed through the sedimentation and burial of terrestrial organisms under high heat and pressure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Organic carbon stored in the geosphere can remain there for millions of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon can leave the geosphere in several ways.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide is released during the metamorphism of carbonate rocks when they are subducted into the Earth's mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This carbon dioxide can be released into the atmosphere and ocean through volcanoes and hotspots.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It can also be removed by humans through the direct extraction of kerogens in the form of fossil fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] After extraction, fossil fuels are burned to release energy and emit the carbon they store into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] There is a fast and a slow carbon cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The fast cycle operates in the biosphere and the slow cycle operates in rocks.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The fast or biological cycle can complete within years, moving carbon from atmosphere to biosphere, then back to the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The slow or geological cycle may extend deep into the mantle and can take millions of years to complete, moving carbon through the Earth's crust between rocks, soil, ocean and atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The fast carbon cycle involves relatively short-term biogeochemical processes between the environment and living organisms in the biosphere (see diagram at start of article).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] It includes movements of carbon between the atmosphere and terrestrial and marine ecosystems, as well as soils and seafloor sediments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The fast cycle includes annual cycles involving photosynthesis and decadal cycles involving vegetative growth and decomposition.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The reactions of the fast carbon cycle to human activities will determine many of the more immediate impacts of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The slow (or deep) carbon cycle involves medium to long-term geochemical processes belonging to the rock cycle (see diagram on the right).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The exchange between the ocean and atmosphere can take centuries, and the weathering of rocks can take millions of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon in the ocean precipitates to the ocean floor where it can form sedimentary rock and be subducted into the Earth's mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Mountain building processes result in the return of this geologic carbon to the Earth's surface.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] There the rocks are weathered and carbon is returned to the atmosphere by degassing and to the ocean by rivers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Other geologic carbon returns to the ocean through the hydrothermal emission of calcium ions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In a given year between 10 and 100 million tonnes of carbon moves around this slow cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This includes volcanoes returning geologic carbon directly to the atmosphere in the form of carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] However, this is less than one percent of the carbon dioxide put into the atmosphere by burning fossil fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Raindrops absorb organic and inorganic carbon through particle scavenging and adsorption of organic vapors while falling toward Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Burning and volcanic eruptions produce highly condensed polycyclic aromatic molecules (i.e. black carbon) that is returned to the atmosphere along with greenhouse gases such as CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Terrestrial plants fix atmospheric CO2 through photosynthesis, returning a fraction back to the atmosphere through respiration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Lignin and celluloses represent as much as 80% of the organic carbon in forests and 60% in pastures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Litterfall and root organic carbon mix with sedimentary material to form organic soils where plant-derived and petrogenic organic carbon is both stored and transformed by microbial and fungal activity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Water absorbs plant and settled aerosol-derived dissolved organic carbon (DOC) and dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC) as it passes over forest canopies (i.e. throughfall) and along plant trunks/stems (i.e. stemflow).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Biogeochemical transformations take place as water soaks into soil solution and groundwater reservoirs and overland flow occurs when soils are completely saturated, or rainfall occurs more rapidly than saturation into soils.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Terrestrially-derived macromolecules such as lignin and black carbon are decomposed into smaller components and monomers, ultimately being converted to CO2, metabolic intermediates, or biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Lakes, reservoirs, and floodplains typically store large amounts of organic carbon and sediments, but also experience net heterotrophy in the water column, resulting in a net flux of CO2 to the atmosphere that is roughly one order of magnitude less than rivers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Methane production is also typically high in the anoxic sediments of floodplains, lakes, and reservoirs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Primary production is typically enhanced in river plumes due to the export of fluvial nutrients.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Nevertheless, estuarine waters are a source of CO2 to the atmosphere, globally.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Coastal marshes both store and export blue carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Marshes and wetlands are suggested to have an equivalent flux of CO2 to the atmosphere as rivers, globally.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Continental shelves and the open ocean typically absorb CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The marine biological pump sequesters a small but significant fraction of the absorbed CO2 as organic carbon in marine sediments (see below).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Terrestrial and marine ecosystems are chiefly connected through riverine transport, which acts as the main channel through which erosive terrestrially derived substances enter into oceanic systems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Material and energy exchanges between the terrestrial biosphere and the lithosphere as well as organic carbon fixation and oxidation processes together regulate ecosystem carbon and dioxygen (O2) pools.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Riverine transport, being the main connective channel of these pools, will act to transport net primary productivity (primarily in the form of dissolved organic carbon (DOC) and particulate organic carbon (POC)) from terrestrial to oceanic systems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] During transport, part of DOC will rapidly return to the atmosphere through redox reactions, causing "carbon degassing" to occur between land-atmosphere storage layers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The remaining DOC and dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC) are also exported to the ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In 2015, inorganic and organic carbon export fluxes from global rivers were assessed as 0.50–0.70 Pg C y−1 and 0.15–0.35 Pg C y−1 respectively.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] On the other hand, POC can remain buried in sediment over an extensive period, and the annual global terrestrial to oceanic POC flux has been estimated at 0.20 (+0.13,-0.07) Gg C y−1.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The ocean biological pump is the ocean's biologically driven sequestration of carbon from the atmosphere and land runoff to the deep ocean interior and seafloor sediments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The biological pump is not so much the result of a single process, but rather the sum of a number of processes each of which can influence biological pumping.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The pump transfers about 11 billion tonnes of carbon every year into the ocean's interior.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] An ocean without the biological pump would result in atmospheric CO2 levels about 400 ppm higher than the present day.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Most carbon incorporated in organic and inorganic biological matter is formed at the sea surface where it can then start sinking to the ocean floor.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The deep ocean gets most of its nutrients from the higher water column when they sink down in the form of marine snow.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This is made up of dead or dying animals and microbes, fecal matter, sand and other inorganic material.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The biological pump is responsible for transforming dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC) into organic biomass and pumping it in particulate or dissolved form into the deep ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Inorganic nutrients and carbon dioxide are fixed during photosynthesis by phytoplankton, which both release dissolved organic matter (DOM) and are consumed by herbivorous zooplankton.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Larger zooplankton - such as copepods, egest fecal pellets - which can be reingested, and sink or collect with other organic detritus into larger, more-rapidly-sinking aggregates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] DOM is partially consumed by bacteria and respired; the remaining refractory DOM is advected and mixed into the deep sea.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] DOM and aggregates exported into the deep water are consumed and respired, thus returning organic carbon into the enormous deep ocean reservoir of DIC.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] A single phytoplankton cell has a sinking rate around one metre per day.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Given that the average depth of the ocean is about four kilometres, it can take over ten years for these cells to reach the ocean floor.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] However, through processes such as coagulation and expulsion in predator fecal pellets, these cells form aggregates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] These aggregates have sinking rates orders of magnitude greater than individual cells and complete their journey to the deep in a matter of days.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] About 1% of the particles leaving the surface ocean reach the seabed and are consumed, respired, or buried in the sediments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The net effect of these processes is to remove carbon in organic form from the surface and return it to DIC at greater depths, maintaining a surface-to-deep ocean gradient of DIC.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Thermohaline circulation returns deep-ocean DIC to the atmosphere on millennial timescales.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The carbon buried in the sediments can be subducted into the Earth's mantle and stored for millions of years as part of the slow carbon cycle (see next section).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Viruses act as "regulators" of the fast carbon cycle because they impact the material cycles and energy flows of food webs and the microbial loop.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The average contribution of viruses to the Earth ecosystem carbon cycle is 8.6%, of which its contribution to marine ecosystems (1.4%) is less than its contribution to terrestrial (6.7%) and freshwater (17.8%) ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Over the past 2,000 years, anthropogenic activities and climate change have gradually altered the regulatory role of viruses in ecosystem carbon cycling processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This has been particularly conspicuous over the past 200 years due to rapid industrialization and the attendant population growth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Slow or deep carbon cycling is an important process, though it is not as well-understood as the relatively fast carbon movement through the atmosphere, terrestrial biosphere, ocean, and geosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The deep carbon cycle is intimately connected to the movement of carbon in the Earth's surface and atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] If the process did not exist, carbon would remain in the atmosphere, where it would accumulate to extremely high levels over long periods of time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Therefore, by allowing carbon to return to the Earth, the deep carbon cycle plays a critical role in maintaining the terrestrial conditions necessary for life to exist.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Furthermore, the process is also significant simply due to the massive quantities of carbon it transports through the planet.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In fact, studying the composition of basaltic magma and measuring carbon dioxide flux out of volcanoes reveals that the amount of carbon in the mantle is actually greater than that on the Earth's surface by a factor of one thousand.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Drilling down and physically observing deep-Earth carbon processes is evidently extremely difficult, as the lower mantle and core extend from 660 to 2,891 km and 2,891 to 6,371 km deep into the Earth respectively.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Accordingly, not much is conclusively known regarding the role of carbon in the deep Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Nonetheless, several pieces of evidence—many of which come from laboratory simulations of deep Earth conditions—have indicated mechanisms for the element's movement down into the lower mantle, as well as the forms that carbon takes at the extreme temperatures and pressures of said layer.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Furthermore, techniques like seismology have led to a greater understanding of the potential presence of carbon in the Earth's core.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon principally enters the mantle in the form of carbonate-rich sediments on tectonic plates of ocean crust, which pull the carbon into the mantle upon undergoing subduction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Not much is known about carbon circulation in the mantle, especially in the deep Earth, but many studies have attempted to augment our understanding of the element's movement and forms within the region.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] For instance, a 2011 study demonstrated that carbon cycling extends all the way to the lower mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The study analyzed rare, super-deep diamonds at a site in Juina, Brazil, determining that the bulk composition of some of the diamonds' inclusions matched the expected result of basalt melting and crystallisation under lower mantle temperatures and pressures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Thus, the investigation's findings indicate that pieces of basaltic oceanic lithosphere act as the principle transport mechanism for carbon to Earth's deep interior.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] These subducted carbonates can interact with lower mantle silicates, eventually forming super-deep diamonds like the one found.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] However, carbonates descending to the lower mantle encounter other fates in addition to forming diamonds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In 2011, carbonates were subjected to an environment similar to that of 1800 km deep into the Earth, well within the lower mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Doing so resulted in the formations of magnesite, siderite, and numerous varieties of graphite.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Other experiments—as well as petrologic observations—support this claim, indicating that magnesite is actually the most stable carbonate phase in most part of the mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This is largely a result of its higher melting temperature.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Consequently, scientists have concluded that carbonates undergo reduction as they descend into the mantle before being stabilised at depth by low oxygen fugacity environments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Magnesium, iron, and other metallic compounds act as buffers throughout the process.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The presence of reduced, elemental forms of carbon like graphite would indicate that carbon compounds are reduced as they descend into the mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Polymorphism alters carbonate compounds' stability at different depths within the Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] To illustrate, laboratory simulations and density functional theory calculations suggest that tetrahedrally coordinated carbonates are most stable at depths approaching the core–mantle boundary.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] A 2015 study indicates that the lower mantle's high pressure causes carbon bonds to transition from sp2 to sp3 hybridised orbitals, resulting in carbon tetrahedrally bonding to oxygen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] CO3 trigonal groups cannot form polymerisable networks, while tetrahedral CO4 can, signifying an increase in carbon's coordination number, and therefore drastic changes in carbonate compounds' properties in the lower mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] As an example, preliminary theoretical studies suggest that high pressure causes carbonate melt viscosity to increase; the melts' lower mobility as a result of its increased viscosity causes large deposits of carbon deep into the mantle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Accordingly, carbon can remain in the lower mantle for long periods of time, but large concentrations of carbon frequently find their way back to the lithosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This process, called carbon outgassing, is the result of carbonated mantle undergoing decompression melting, as well as mantle plumes carrying carbon compounds up towards the crust.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon is oxidised upon its ascent towards volcanic hotspots, where it is then released as CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] This occurs so that the carbon atom matches the oxidation state of the basalts erupting in such areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Although the presence of carbon in the Earth's core is well-constrained, recent studies suggest large inventories of carbon could be stored in this region.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Shear (S) waves moving through the inner core travel at about fifty percent of the velocity expected for most iron-rich alloys.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Because the core's composition is believed to be an alloy of crystalline iron and a small amount of nickel, this seismic anomaly indicates the presence of light elements, including carbon, in the core.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In fact, studies using diamond anvil cells to replicate the conditions in the Earth's core indicate that iron carbide (Fe7C3) matches the inner core's wave speed and density.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Therefore, the iron carbide model could serve as an evidence that the core holds as much as 67% of the Earth's carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Furthermore, another study found that in the pressure and temperature condition of the Earth's inner core, carbon dissolved in iron and formed a stable phase with the same Fe7C3 composition—albeit with a different structure from the one previously mentioned.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] In summary, although the amount of carbon potentially stored in the Earth's core is not known, recent studies indicate that the presence of iron carbides can explain some of the geophysical observations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Since the Industrial Revolution, and especially since the end of WWII, human activity has substantially disturbed the global carbon cycle by redistributing massive amounts of carbon from the geosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Humans have also continued to shift the natural component functions of the terrestrial biosphere with changes to vegetation and other land use.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Man-made (synthetic) carbon compounds have been designed and mass-manufactured that will persist for decades to millennia in air, water, and sediments as pollutants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Climate change is amplifying and forcing further indirect human changes to the carbon cycle as a consequence of various positive and negative feedbacks.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Current trends in climate change lead to higher ocean temperatures and acidity, thus modifying marine ecosystems.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Also, acid rain and polluted runoff from agriculture and industry change the ocean's chemical composition.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Such changes can have dramatic effects on highly sensitive ecosystems such as coral reefs, thus limiting the ocean's ability to absorb carbon from the atmosphere on a regional scale and reducing oceanic biodiversity globally.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The exchanges of carbon between the atmosphere and other components of the Earth system, collectively known as the carbon cycle, currently constitute important negative (dampening) feedbacks on the effect of anthropogenic carbon emissions on climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon sinks in the land and the ocean each currently take up about one-quarter of anthropogenic carbon emissions each year.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] These feedbacks are expected to weaken in the future, amplifying the effect of anthropogenic carbon emissions on climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The degree to which they will weaken, however, is highly uncertain, with Earth system models predicting a wide range of land and ocean carbon uptakes even under identical atmospheric concentration or emission scenarios.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Arctic methane emissions indirectly caused by anthropogenic global warming also affect the carbon cycle and contribute to further warming.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] The largest and one of the fastest growing human impacts on the carbon cycle and biosphere is the extraction and burning of fossil fuels, which directly transfer carbon from the geosphere into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Carbon dioxide is also produced and released during the calcination of limestone for clinker production.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Clinker is an industrial precursor of cement.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] As of 2020, about 450 gigatons of fossil carbon have been extracted in total; an amount approaching the carbon contained in all of Earth's living terrestrial biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Recent rates of global emissions directly into the atmosphere have exceeded the uptake by vegetation and the oceans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] These sinks have been expected and observed to remove about half of the added atmospheric carbon within about a century.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Nevertheless, sinks like the ocean have evolving saturation properties, and a substantial fraction (20–35%, based on coupled models) of the added carbon is projected to remain in the atmosphere for centuries to millennia.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Halocarbons are less prolific compounds developed for diverse uses throughout industry; for example as solvents and refrigerants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Chlorofluorocarbons also cause stratospheric ozone depletion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] International efforts are ongoing under the Montreal Protocol and Kyoto Protocol to control rapid growth in the industrial manufacturing and use of these environmentally potent gases.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] For some applications more benign alternatives such as hydrofluoroolefins have been developed and are being gradually introduced.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Since the invention of agriculture, humans have directly and gradually influenced the carbon cycle over century-long timescales by modifying the mixture of vegetation in the terrestrial biosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Over the past several centuries, direct and indirect human-caused land use and land cover change (LUCC) has led to the loss of biodiversity, which lowers ecosystems' resilience to environmental stresses and decreases their ability to remove carbon from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] More directly, it often leads to the release of carbon from terrestrial ecosystems into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Deforestation for agricultural purposes removes forests, which hold large amounts of carbon, and replaces them, generally with agricultural or urban areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] Both of these replacement land cover types store comparatively small amounts of carbon so that the net result of the transition is that more carbon stays in the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-cycle] However, the effects on the atmosphere and overall carbon cycle can be intentionally and/or naturally reversed with reforestation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Biologic carbon sequestration is a naturally occurring process as part of the carbon cycle.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Humans can enhance it through deliberate actions and use of technology.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide (CO 2) is naturally captured from the atmosphere through biological, chemical, and physical processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These processes can be accelerated for example through changes in land use and agricultural practices, called carbon farming.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Artificial processes have also been devised to produce similar effects.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This approach is called carbon capture and storage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It involves using technology to capture and sequester (store) CO 2 that is produced from human activities underground or under the sea bed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Plants absorb carbon dioxide from the air as they grow, and bind it into biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, biological stores (such as forests and kelp beds) may be temporary carbon sinks, as long-term sequestration cannot be guaranteed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Wildfires, disease, economic pressures, and changing political priorities may release the sequestered carbon back into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide that has been removed from the atmosphere can also be stored in the Earth's crust by injecting it underground, or in the form of insoluble carbonate salts.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The latter process is called mineral sequestration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These methods are considered *non-volatile* because they not only remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere but also sequester it indefinitely.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This means the carbon is "locked away" for thousands to millions of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] To enhance carbon sequestration processes in oceans the following chemical or physical technologies have been proposed: ocean fertilization, artificial upwelling, basalt storage, mineralization, deep-sea sediments, and adding bases to neutralize acids.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, none have achieved large scale application so far.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Large-scale seaweed farming on the other hand is a biological process and could sequester significant amounts of carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The potential growth of seaweed for carbon farming would see the harvested seaweed transported to the deep ocean for long-term burial.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" on seaweed farming as a mitigation tactic.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The term *carbon sequestration* has diverse meanings in the literature and media.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines carbon sequestration as "The process of storing carbon in a carbon pool".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Subsequently, a *pool* is defined as "a reservoir in the Earth system where elements, such as carbon and nitrogen, reside in various chemical forms for a period of time".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon sequestration is part of the natural carbon cycle by which carbon is exchanged among the biosphere, pedosphere (soil), geosphere, hydrosphere, and atmosphere of Earth.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide is naturally captured from the atmosphere through biological, chemical, or physical processes, and stored in long-term reservoirs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, biological stores (such as forests and kelp beds) are considered *volatile carbon sinks* as long-term sequestration cannot be guaranteed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Events such as wildfires or disease, economic pressures, and changing political priorities can result in the sequestered carbon being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon sequestration, which acts as a carbon sink, helps to mitigate climate change and thus reduce harmful effects of climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It helps to slow the atmospheric and marine accumulation of greenhouse gases, which is mainly carbon dioxide released by burning fossil fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon sequestration for climate change mitigation can involve either enhancing natural carbon sinks or employing technological methods to capture and store carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Within the carbon capture and storage approaches, *carbon sequestration* refers to the *storage* component.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Artificial carbon storage technologies can be applied, such as gaseous storage in deep geological formations (including saline formations and exhausted gas fields), and solid storage by reaction of CO2 with metal oxides to produce stable carbonates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For carbon to be sequestered artificially—that is, outside the natural processes of the carbon cycle—it must first be captured, or its release into the atmosphere must be significantly delayed or prevented.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This can be achieved by incorporating carbon-rich materials into long-lasting applications, such as construction, thereby avoiding release through processes like combustion or decay.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Thereafter it can be passively stored or remain productively utilized over time in a variety of ways.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For instance, upon harvesting, wood (as a carbon-rich material) can be incorporated into construction or a range of other durable products, thus sequestering its carbon over years or even centuries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In industrial production, engineers typically capture carbon dioxide from emissions from power plants or factories.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The document emphasized the importance of farmers, landowners, and coastal communities in carbon sequestration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It directed the Treasury Department to promote conservation of carbon sinks through market based mechanisms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Noting that the planet's carbon sequestration capacity is not unlimited, a 2025 study concluded that fully using Earth's geologic storage capacity would help limit global warming by only 0.7 °C (1.3 °F).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Biological carbon sequestration (also called *biosequestration*) is the capture and storage of the atmospheric greenhouse gas carbon dioxide by continual and enhanced biological processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This form of carbon sequestration occurs through increased rates of photosynthesis via land-use practices such as reforestation and sustainable forest management.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Land-use changes that enhance natural carbon capture have the potential to capture and store large amounts of carbon dioxide each year.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These include the conservation, management, and restoration of ecosystems such as forests, peatlands, wetlands, and grasslands, in addition to carbon sequestration methods in agriculture.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Methods and practices exist to enhance soil carbon sequestration in both agriculture and forestry.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Wetland restoration involves restoring a wetland's natural biological, geological, and chemical functions through re-establishment or rehabilitation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It is a good way to reduce climate change.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Wetland soil, particularly in coastal wetlands such as mangroves, sea grasses, and salt marshes, is an important carbon reservoir; 20–30% of the world's soil carbon is found in wetlands, while only 5–8% of the world's land is composed of wetlands.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Studies have shown that restored wetlands can become productive CO2 sinks and many are being restored.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Aside from climate benefits, wetland restoration and conservation can help preserve biodiversity, improve water quality, and aid with flood control.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The plants that make up wetlands absorb carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere and convert it into organic matter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The waterlogged nature of the soil slows down the decomposition of organic material, resulting in the accumulation of carbon-rich sediments, that act as a long-term carbon sink.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Additionally, anaerobic conditions in waterlogged soils hinder the complete breakdown of organic matter, promoting the conversion of carbon into more stable forms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] As with forests, for the sequestration process to succeed, the wetland must remain undisturbed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If it is disturbed the carbon stored in the plants and sediments will be released back into the atmosphere, and the ecosystem will no longer function as a carbon sink.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Additionally, some wetlands can release non-CO2 greenhouse gases, such as methane and nitrous oxide which could offset potential climate benefits.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The amounts of carbon sequestered via blue carbon by wetlands can also be difficult to measure.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Wetland soil is an important carbon sink; 14.5% of the world's soil carbon is found in wetlands, while only 5.5% of the world's land is composed of wetlands.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Not only are wetlands a great carbon sink, they have many other benefits like collecting floodwater, filtering out air and water pollutants, and creating a home for numerous birds, fish, insects, and plants.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Climate change could alter wetland soil carbon storage, changing it from a sink to a source.With rising temperatures comes an increase in greenhouse gasses from wetlands especially locations with permafrost.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When this permafrost melts it increases the available oxygen and water in the soil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Because of this, bacteria in the soil would create large amounts of carbon dioxide and methane to be released into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The link between climate change and wetlands is still not fully known.It is also not clear how restored wetlands manage carbon while still being a contributing source of methane.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, preserving these areas would help prevent further release of carbon into the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Despite occupying only 3% of the global land area, peatlands hold approximately 30% of the carbon in our ecosystem - twice the amount stored in the world's forests.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Most peatlands are situated in high latitude areas of the northern hemisphere, with most of their growth occurring since the last ice age, but they are also found in tropical regions, such as the Amazon and Congo Basin.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Peatlands grow steadily over thousands of years, accumulating dead plant material – and the carbon contained within it – due to waterlogged conditions which greatly slow rates of decay.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If peatlands are drained, for farmland or development, the plant material stored within them decomposes rapidly, releasing stored carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These degraded peatlands account for 5-10% of global carbon emissions from human activities.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The loss of one peatland could potentially produce more carbon than 175–500 years of methane emissions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Peatland protection and restoration are therefore important measures to mitigate carbon emissions, and also provide benefits for biodiversity, freshwater provision, and flood risk reduction.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Compared to natural vegetation, cropland soils are depleted in soil organic carbon (SOC).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When soil is converted from natural land or semi-natural land, such as forests, woodlands, grasslands, steppes, and savannas, the SOC content in the soil reduces by about 30–40%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This loss is due to harvesting, as plants contain carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When land use changes, the carbon in the soil will either increase or decrease, and this change will continue until the soil reaches a new equilibrium.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Deviations from this equilibrium can also be affected by variated climate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The decreasing of SOC content can be counteracted by increasing the carbon input.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This can be done with several strategies, e.g. leave harvest residues on the field, use manure as fertilizer, or include perennial crops in the rotation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Perennial crops have a larger below-ground biomass fraction, which increases the SOC content.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Perennial crops reduce the need for tillage and thus help mitigate soil erosion, and may help increase soil organic matter.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Globally, soils are estimated to contain >8,580 gigatons of organic carbon, about ten times the amount in the atmosphere and much more than in vegetation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Researchers have found that rising temperatures can lead to population booms in soil microbes, converting stored carbon into carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In laboratory experiments heating soil, fungi-rich soils released less carbon dioxide than other soils.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Following carbon dioxide (CO2) absorption from the atmosphere, plants deposit organic matter into the soil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This organic matter, derived from decaying plant material and root systems, is rich in carbon compounds.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Microorganisms in the soil break down this organic matter, and in the process, some of the carbon becomes further stabilized in the soil as humus - a process known as humification.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] On a global basis, it is estimated that soil contains about 2,500 gigatons of carbon.This is greater than 3-fold the carbon found in the atmosphere and 4-fold of that found in living plants and animals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] About 70% of the global soil organic carbon in non-permafrost areas is found in the deeper soil within the upper metre and is stabilized by mineral-organic associations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon farming is a set of agricultural methods that aim to store carbon in the soil and biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The technical term for this is *carbon sequestration*.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The overall goal of carbon farming is to create a net loss of carbon from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This is done by increasing the rate at which carbon is sequestered into soil and plant material.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The increase of biomass from roots and the soil's microbiome leads to an increase in the organic matter content of the soil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Increasing organic matter content in soils aids plant growth, improves soil water retention capacity and reduces fertilizer use.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Sustainable forest management is another tool that is used in carbon farming.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon farming is one component of climate-smart agriculture.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It is also one way to remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Agricultural methods for carbon farming include adjusting how tillage and livestock grazing is done, using organic mulch or compost, working with biochar and terra preta, and changing the crop types.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Methods used in forestry include reforestation and bamboo farming.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] As of 2016, variants of carbon farming reached hundreds of millions of hectares globally, of the nearly 5 billion hectares (1.2×1010 acres) of world farmland.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon farming tends to be more expensive than conventional agricultural practices.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Depending on the region, carbon farmings costs US$3-130 per tonne of carbon dioxide sequestered.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Some countries provide subsidies to farmers to use carbon farming methods.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] While the implementation of carbon farming methods can reduce/sequester emissions, it is important to also consider the effects of land use changes with respect to the conversion of forests to agricultural production.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Prairie restoration is a conservation effort to restore prairie lands that were destroyed due to industrial, agricultural, commercial, or residential development.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The primary aim is to return areas and ecosystems to their previous state before their depletion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The mass of SOC able to be stored in these restored plots is typically greater than the previous crop, acting as a more effective carbon sink.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Biochar is charcoal created by pyrolysis of biomass waste.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The resulting material is added to a landfill or used as a soil improver to create terra preta.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Adding biochar may increase the soil-C stock for the long term and so mitigate global warming by offsetting the atmospheric C (up to 9.5 Gigatons C annually).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In the soil, the biochar carbon is unavailable for oxidation to CO 2 and consequential atmospheric release.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However concerns have been raised about biochar potentially accelerating release of the carbon already present in the soil.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Terra preta, an anthropogenic, high-carbon soil, is also being investigated as a sequestration mechanism.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] By pyrolysing biomass, about half of its carbon can be reduced to charcoal, which can persist in the soil for centuries, and makes a useful soil amendment, especially in tropical soils (*biochar* or *agrichar*).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Burying biomass (such as trees) directly mimics the natural processes that created fossil fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The global potential for carbon sequestration using wood burial is estimated to be 10 ± 5 GtC/yr and largest rates in tropical forests (4.2 GtC/yr), followed by temperate (3.7 GtC/yr) and boreal forests (2.1 GtC/yr).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In 2008, Ning Zeng of the University of Maryland estimated 65 GtC lying on the floor of the world's forests as coarse woody material which could be buried and costs for wood burial carbon sequestration run at US$50/tC which is much lower than carbon capture from e.g. power plant emissions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] CO2 fixation into woody biomass is a natural process carried out through photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This is a nature-based solution and methods being trialled include the use of "wood vaults" to store the wood-containing carbon under oxygen-free conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In 2022, a certification organization published methodologies for biomass burial.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Other biomass storage proposals have included the burial of biomass deep underwater, including at the bottom of the Black Sea.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Geological sequestration refers to the storage of CO2 underground in depleted oil and gas reservoirs, saline formations, or deep, coal beds unsuitable for mining.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Once CO2 is captured from a point source, such as a cement factory, it can be compressed to ≈100 bar into a supercritical fluid.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In this form, the CO2 could be transported via pipeline to the place of storage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The CO2 could then be injected deep underground, typically around 1 km (0.6 mi), where it would be stable for hundreds to millions of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Under these storage conditions, the density of supercritical CO2 is 600 to 800 kg/m3.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The important parameters in determining a good site for carbon storage are: rock porosity, rock permeability, absence of faults, and geometry of rock layers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The medium in which the CO2 is to be stored ideally has a high porosity and permeability, such as sandstone or limestone.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Sandstone can have a permeability ranging from 1 to 10−5 Darcy, with a porosity as high as ≈30%.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The porous rock must be capped by a layer of low permeability, which function as a seal, or caprock, for the CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Shale is an example of a very good caprock, with a permeability of 10−5 to 10−9 Darcy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Once injected, the CO2 plume will rise via buoyant forces, since it is less dense than its surroundings.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Once it encounters a caprock, it will spread laterally until it encounters a gap.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If there are fault planes near the injection zone, there is a possibility the CO2 could migrate along the fault to the surface, leaking into the atmosphere, which would be potentially dangerous to life in the surrounding area.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Another risk related to carbon sequestration is induced seismicity.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If the injection of CO2 creates pressures underground that are too high, the formation will fracture, potentially causing an earthquake.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Structural trapping is considered the principal storage mechanism, impermeable or low permeability rocks such as mudstone, anhydrite, halite, or impermeable carbonates act as a barrier to the upward buoyant migration of CO2, resulting in the retention of CO2 within a storage formation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] While trapped in a rock formation, CO2 can be in the supercritical fluid phase or dissolve in groundwater/brine.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It can also react with minerals in the geologic formation to become carbonates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In 2025, research indicated that, of nearly 12,000 GtCO2 of theoretical carbon storage capacity, just 1,460 GtCO2 is risk-free, significantly less than most estimates suggested.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Mineral sequestration aims to trap carbon in the form of solid carbonate salts.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This process occurs slowly in nature and is responsible for the deposition and accumulation of limestone over geologic time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbonic acid in groundwater slowly reacts with complex silicates to dissolve calcium, magnesium, alkalis and silica and leave a residue of clay minerals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The dissolved calcium and magnesium react with bicarbonate to precipitate calcium and magnesium carbonates, a process that organisms use to make shells.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When the organisms die, their shells are deposited as sediment and eventually turn into limestone.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Limestones have accumulated over billions of years of geologic time and contain much of Earth's carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Ongoing research aims to speed up similar reactions involving alkali carbonates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Zeolitic imidazolate frameworks (ZIFs) are metal–organic frameworks similar to zeolites.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Because of their porosity, chemical stability and thermal resistance, ZIFs are being examined for their capacity to capture carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] CO2 exothermically reacts with metal oxides, producing stable carbonates (e.g. calcite, magnesite).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This process (CO2-to-stone) occurs naturally over periods of years and is responsible for much surface limestone.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Rocks rich in metal oxides that react with CO2, such as MgO and CaO as contained in basalts, have been proven as a viable means to achieve carbon-dioxide mineral storage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The reaction rate can in principle be accelerated with a catalyst or by increasing pressures, or by mineral pre-treatment, although this method can require additional energy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Ultramafic mine tailings are a readily available source of fine-grained metal oxides that could serve this purpose.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Accelerating passive CO2 sequestration via mineral carbonation may be achieved through microbial processes that enhance mineral dissolution and carbonate precipitation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon, in the form of CO 2 can be removed from the atmosphere by chemical processes, and stored in stable carbonate mineral forms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This process (CO 2-to-stone) is known as "carbon sequestration by mineral carbonation" or mineral sequestration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The process involves reacting carbon dioxide with abundantly available metal oxides – either magnesium oxide (MgO) or calcium oxide (CaO) – to form stable carbonates.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These reactions are exothermic and occur naturally (e.g., the weathering of rock over geologic time periods).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Calcium and magnesium are found in nature typically as calcium and magnesium silicates (such as forsterite and serpentinite) and not as binary oxides.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These reactions are slightly more favorable at low temperatures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This process occurs naturally over geologic time frames and is responsible for much of the Earth's surface limestone.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The reaction rate can be made faster however, by reacting at higher temperatures and/or pressures, although this method requires some additional energy.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Alternatively, the mineral could be milled to increase its surface area, and exposed to water and constant abrasion to remove the inert silica as could be achieved naturally by dumping olivine in the high energy surf of beaches.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When CO 2 is dissolved in water and injected into hot basaltic rocks underground it has been shown that the CO 2 reacts with the basalt to form solid carbonate minerals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] A test plant in Iceland started up in October 2017, extracting up to 50 tons of CO2 a year from the atmosphere and storing it underground in basaltic rock.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Several start-ups are trying to do this at scale.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The ocean sequesters carbon through diverse processes.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The solubility pump moves carbon dioxide from the atmosphere into the surface ocean where it reacts with water molecules to form carbonic acid.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The solubility of carbon dioxide increases with decreasing water temperatures.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Thermohaline circulation moves dissolved carbon dioxide to cooler waters where it is more soluble, increasing carbon concentrations in the ocean interior.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The biological pump moves dissolved carbon dioxide from the surface ocean to the ocean's interior through the conversion of inorganic carbon to organic carbon by photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Organic matter that survives respiration and remineralization can be transported through sinking particles and organism migration to the deep ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The low temperatures, high pressure, and reduced oxygen levels in the deep sea slow down decomposition processes, preventing the rapid release of carbon back into the atmosphere and acting as a long-term storage reservoir.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Blue carbon is a concept within climate change mitigation that refers to "biologically driven carbon fluxes and storage in marine systems that are amenable to management".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Most commonly, it refers to the role that tidal marshes, mangroves and seagrass meadows can play in carbon sequestration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Whether macroalgae (seaweeds) can be considered blue carbon ecosystems remains contentious.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These ecosystems can play an important role for climate change mitigation and ecosystem-based adaptation.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, when blue carbon ecosystems are degraded or lost, they release carbon back to the atmosphere, thereby adding to greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Seaweed grows in shallow and coastal areas, and captures significant amounts of carbon that can be transported to the deep ocean by oceanic mechanisms; seaweed reaching the deep ocean sequester carbon and prevent it from exchanging with the atmosphere over millennia.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Growing seaweed offshore with the purpose of sinking the seaweed in the depths of the sea to sequester carbon has been suggested.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In addition, seaweed grows very fast and can theoretically be harvested and processed to generate biomethane, via anaerobic digestion to generate electricity, via cogeneration/CHP or as a replacement for natural gas.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Both macroalgae and microalgae are being investigated as possible means of carbon sequestration.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Marine phytoplankton perform half of the global photosynthetic CO2 fixation (net global primary production of ~50 Pg C per year) and half of the oxygen production despite amounting to only ~1% of global plant biomass.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Because algae lack the complex lignin associated with terrestrial plants, the carbon in algae is released into the atmosphere more rapidly than carbon captured on land.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Algae have been proposed as a short-term storage pool of carbon that can be used as a feedstock for the production of various biogenic fuels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Large-scale seaweed farming could sequester significant amounts of carbon.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Wild seaweed will sequester large amount of carbon through dissolved particles of organic matter being transported to deep ocean seafloors where it will become buried and remain for long periods of time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] With respect to carbon farming, the potential growth of seaweed for carbon farming would see the harvested seaweed transported to the deep ocean for long-term burial.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Seaweed farming occurs mostly in the Asian Pacific coastal areas where it has been a rapidly increasing market.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Ocean fertilization or ocean nourishment refers to both natural and intentional processes that replenish iron and other nutrients in the upper ocean, which in turn stimulate the growth of phytoplankton and in some circumstances draw down large amounts of carbon dioxide (CO2) through photosynthesis.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Intentional ocean fertilization is biomimicry of natural processes that have removed atmospheric CO2 before ice ages as well as after volcanic eruptions, whale defecation, and near hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The introduction of nutrients to the upper ocean increases marine food production as well as removing carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] A number of techniques, including fertilization by the micronutrient iron (called "ocean iron fertilization" or OIF) or with nitrogen and phosphorus (both macronutrients), have been proposed.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Ocean iron fertilization can stimulate photosynthesis in phytoplankton.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The phytoplankton converts the ocean's dissolved carbon dioxide into carbohydrate, some of which has been shown to sink into the deeper ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] More than a dozen open-sea experiments confirmed that adding iron to the ocean increases photosynthesis in phytoplankton by up to 30 times.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Artificial upwelling or downwelling is an approach that would change the mixing layers of the ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Encouraging various ocean layers to mix can move nutrients and dissolved gases around.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Mixing may be achieved by placing large vertical pipes in the oceans to pump nutrient-rich water to the surface, triggering blooms of algae, which store carbon when they grow and export carbon when they die.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This produces results somewhat similar to iron fertilization.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] One side-effect is a short-term rise in CO 2, which limits its attractiveness.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Mixing layers involve transporting the denser and colder deep ocean water to the surface mixed layer.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] As the ocean temperature decreases with depth, more carbon dioxide and other compounds are able to dissolve in the deeper layers.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This can be induced by reversing the oceanic carbon cycle through the use of large vertical pipes serving as ocean pumps, or a mixer array.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] When the nutrient rich deep ocean water is moved to the surface, algae bloom occurs, resulting in a decrease in carbon dioxide due to carbon intake from phytoplankton and other photosynthetic eukaryotic organisms.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The transfer of heat between the layers will also cause seawater from the mixed layer to sink and absorb more carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This method has not gained much traction as algae bloom harms marine ecosystems by blocking sunlight and releasing harmful toxins into the ocean.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The sudden increase in carbon dioxide on the surface level will also temporarily decrease the pH of the seawater, impairing the growth of coral reefs.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The production of carbonic acid through the dissolution of carbon dioxide in seawater hinders marine biogenic calcification and causes major disruptions to the oceanic food chain.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide sequestration in basalt involves the injecting of CO 2 into deep-sea formations.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The CO 2 first mixes with seawater and then reacts with the basalt, both of which are alkaline-rich elements.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This reaction results in the release of Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions forming stable carbonate minerals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Underwater basalt offers a good alternative to other forms of oceanic carbon storage because it has a number of trapping measures to ensure added protection against leakage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] These measures include "geochemical, sediment, gravitational and hydrate formation." Because CO 2 hydrate is denser than CO 2 in seawater, the risk of leakage is minimal.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Injecting the CO 2 at depths greater than 2,700 meters (8,900 ft) ensures that the CO 2 has a greater density than seawater, causing it to sink.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] One possible injection site is Juan de Fuca Plate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Researchers at the Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory found that this plate at the western coast of the United States has a possible storage capacity of 208 gigatons.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This could cover the entire current U.S. carbon emissions for over 100 years (as of 2009).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] This process is undergoing tests as part of the CarbFix project, resulting in 95% of the injected 250 tonnes of CO2 to solidify into calcite in two years, using 25 tonnes of water per tonne of CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Similar to mineralization processes that take place within rocks, mineralization can also occur under the sea.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The rate of dissolution of carbon dioxide from atmosphere to oceanic regions is determined by the circulation period of the ocean and buffering ability of subducting surface water.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Researchers have demonstrated that the carbon dioxide marine storage at several kilometers depth could be viable for up to 500 years, but is dependent on injection site and conditions.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Several studies have shown that although it may fix carbon dioxide effectively, carbon dioxide may be released back to the atmosphere over time.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, this is unlikely for at least a few more centuries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The neutralization of CaCO3, or balancing the concentration of CaCO3 on the seafloor, land and in the ocean, can be measured on a timescale of thousands of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] More specifically, the predicted time is 1700 years for ocean and approximately 5000 to 6000 years for land.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Further, the dissolution time for CaCO3 can be improved by injecting near or downstream of the storage site.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In addition to carbon mineralization, another proposal is deep sea sediment injection.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It injects liquid carbon dioxide at least 3,000 m (9,800 ft) below the surface directly into ocean sediments to generate carbon dioxide hydrate.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Several research models have shown that the optimal depth of injection requires consideration of intrinsic permeability and any changes in liquid carbon dioxide permeability for optimal storage.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The formation of hydrates decreases liquid carbon dioxide permeability, and injection below HFZ is more energetically favored than within the HFZ.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] If the NBZ is a greater column of water than the HFZ, the injection should happen below the HFZ and directly to the NBZ.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] In this case, liquid carbon dioxide will sink to the NBZ and be stored below the buoyancy and hydrate cap.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide leakage can occur if there is dissolution into pore fluidor via molecular diffusion.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, this occurs over thousands of years.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Carbon dioxide forms carbonic acid when dissolved in water, making ocean acidification a significant consequence of elevated CO 2 levels.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The acidification also limits the rate at which CO 2 can be absorbed by the ocean (through the solubility pump).
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Various bases have been suggested that could neutralize the ocean acidity and thereby enhance CO 2 absorption.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For example, adding crushed limestone to oceans enhances the absorption of carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Another approach involves adding sodium hydroxide, produced through electrolysis of saltwater or brine.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The resulting hydrochloric acid byproduct can be neutralized by reacting it with volcanic silicate rocks, such as enstatite—effectively accelerating the natural weathering process to help restore ocean pH.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Single-step carbon sequestration and storage is a saline water-based mineralization technology extracting carbon dioxide from seawater and storing it in the form of solid minerals.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] It was once suggested that CO2 could be stored in the oceans by direct injection into the deep ocean and storing it there for some centuries.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] At the time, this proposal was called "ocean storage" but more precisely it was known as "direct deep-sea carbon dioxide injection".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, the interest in this avenue of carbon storage has much reduced since about 2001 because of concerns about the unknown impacts on marine life, high costs and concerns about its stability or permanence.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The "IPCC Special Report on Carbon Dioxide Capture and Storage" in 2005 did include this technology as an option.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] However, the IPCC Fifth Assessment Report in 2014 no longer mentioned the term "ocean storage" in its report on climate change mitigation methods.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] The 2022 IPCC Sixth Assessment Report does not mention "ocean storage" in its "Carbon Dioxide Removal taxonomy".
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] Cost of carbon sequestration (not including capture and transport) varies but is below US$10 per tonne in some cases where onshore storage is available.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] For example Carbfix cost is around US$25 per tonne of CO2.
[src:anthropogenic-metabolism/carbon-sequestration] A 2020 report estimated sequestration in forests (so including capture) at US$35 for small quantities to US$280 per tonne for 10% of the total required to keep to 1.5 C warming.
